name: dispense
description: v. to deal out; distribute; to give a service or advice to several recipients; to administer
examples: As nice as it would have been to dispense with the fairy tale tropes altogether, they are necessary here.::They also will not be allowed to dispense medications on site, one of the major draws for the clinics.

name: wrangle
description: v. to argue or dispute, especially in a noisy or angry manner; to obtain something or persuade somebody by arguing persistently
examples: The other portion Obama has managed to wrangle from private donors.::How did you wrangle Nicole Kidman for her hilarious cameo in the movie?

name: edifice
description: n. a building, especially one of large size or imposing appearance; any large, complex system or organization.
examples: It is an edifice that seems to have been constructed for eternity::A gush of smoke came from a chimney in the rear of the edifice

name: authentic
description: adj. not false or copied; genuine; real; shown to be true and trustworthy
examples: By stepping outside myth, the show brought the expectation that it would be something new and authentic.

name: peasant
description: n. an agricultural laborer or small farmer; somebody who lives in the country; an offensive term for somebody considered to be ill-mannered or uneducated
examples: He was a large man, totally bald, with the rough hands of a peasant.

name: ominous
description: adj. suggesting or indicating that something bad is going to happen or be revealed; foreboding; threatening; inauspicious
examples: But the jungle has an ominous feel; one wrong step and it will swallow you whole::The drumbeat and synth bass are as insistent as they are ominous

name: vie
description: v. to strive in competition or rivalry with another; contend for superiority
examples: People seemed to vie with each other in giving away their property

name: prudent
description: adj. wise or judicious in practical affairs; sagacious; discreet or circumspect; sober; careful in providing for the future; provident
examples: prudent pilots avoid them when they can, not simply for safety reasons, but to give us a smoother flight

name: obliterate
description: v. to remove or destroy all traces of; do away with; destroy completely; to blot out or render undecipherable (writing, marks, etc.); efface
examples: Yet to destroy the precious book would be to obliterate centuries of information about the Ma family line

name: traverse
description: v. to travel or move across, over, or through an area or a place; to move backward and forward across something
examples: Maps are enormous, and players have to traverse huge amounts of terrain.::Yet somehow this trend never quite managed to traverse the Atlantic.

name: amend
description: v. to make changes to something, especially a piece of text, in order to improve or correct it; to revise or alter formally a motion, bill, or constitution
examples: Rather than urge taxpayers to amend their tax returns to get a refund, the division does the exact opposite

name: obsequious
description: adj. excessively eager to please or obey; obedient; dutiful
examples: Still, for the last year the media has been treating the Abe regime with obsequious deference.

name: rigor
description: n. strictness, severity, or harshness, as in dealing with people; an experience of great hardship or difficulty; austerity
examples: The difference was enforcement and the rigor of American led efforts in Iraq and European reticence in Bosnia.

name: cogent
description: adj. convincing or believable by virtue of forcible, clear, or incisive presentation; telling; pertinent
examples: The senator was, even more than usual, passionate, cogent, and earnest in his criticisms.

name: nauseous
description: adj. suffering from the unsettling feeling in the stomach that accompanies the urge to vomit
examples: It was in the middle of the night, like two in the morning, and I was so nauseous and they brought me down in the crane.

name: reconnaissance
description: n. preliminary research or investigation of something; the exploration or examination of an area to gather information, especially about the strength and positioning of enemy forces
examples: In 2012, Syria shot down a Turkish military jet that was on a reconnaissance mission off the Syrian coast, killing the two pilots

name: platoon
description: n. a subdivision of a company of soldiers, usually led by a lieutenant and consisting of two to three sections or squads of ten to twelve people; a body of people or things with a common purpose or goal
examples: The soldiers in 2nd platoon, Blackfoot Company discovered his rifle, helmet, body armor and web gear in a neat stack.

name: swirl
description: v. to turn around and around with a twisting or spiraling movement, or make something move in this way; to be dizzy or giddy, as the head
examples: But the swirl of activity around her will reach its fevered pitch on November 24 when her lawyers launch her appeal.

name: reticent
description: adj. unwilling to communicate very much, talk freely, or reveal all the facts about something; unwilling to do something
examples: The New York Times, usually so reticent on sex-scandal stories, has named her and run the picture.

name: spiral
description: n. a plane curve generated by a point moving around a fixed point while constantly receding from or approaching it
examples: He will take them into the lighthouse and up the spiral staircase to the top, which affords a spectacular view of the Arabian Sea.

name: downspin
description: n. a very sudden and sharp reduction
examples: things took a downspin for his entire family

name: relinquish
description: v. to renounce or surrender something; to give up; put aside or desist from; to let go; release
examples: He would not relinquish presidential power and live to regret it, like his cousin.::To be a hero, you must accept your fate and relinquish control to it.

name: diverse
description: adj. of various kinds or forms; multiform; of a different kind, form, character, etc.; unlike
examples: It strengthens our culture, and helps to bring our diverse country together with a healthy dose of nationalism.

name: appraisal
description: n. the act of estimating or judging the nature or value of something or someone
examples: Thomas, however, reveals she is actually far more understanding in her appraisal of Girls

name: analogy
description: n. a comparison between two things that are similar in some way, often used to help explain something or make it easier to understand; similarity or comparability
examples: I see no analogy between your problem and mine

name: germane
description: adj. closely or significantly related; relevant; pertinent
examples: Please keep your statements germane to the issue

name: avocation
description: n.something a person does in addition to a principal occupation, especially for pleasure; hobby; a person's regular occupation, calling, or vocation
examples: He stammered, and read and wrote a lot of poetry (mostly in secret), an avocation he changed to photography for the novel.

name: precarious
description: adj. dependent on circumstances beyond one's control; uncertain; unstable; insecure; based on uncertain premises or unwarranted assumptions
examples: Yes, the Republican Party is in a precarious position, but there are signs of hope out there

name: avalanche
description: n. a rapid downhill flow of a large mass of something dislodged from a mountainside or the top of a precipice, especially snow or ice; a sudden overwhelming quantity of something
examples: And sure enough, right there on the D&G runway was an avalanche of color and patterns and good times.

name: swath
description: n. the space covered by the stroke of a scythe or the cut of a mowing machine; a line or ridge of grass, grain, or the like, cut and thrown together by a scythe or mowing machine
examples: Personal priorities are reshuffling, and your default me-first attitude helps clear a swath of competing obligations

name: capricious
description: adj. tending to make sudden unexpected changes; erratic
examples: He's such a capricious boss I never know how he'll react.

name: heroic
description: adj. showing great bravery, courage, or determination
examples: But in the last few decades, an often heroic group of parents have been pioneers in advocating for their sons and daughters.

name: allure
description: n. an attractive or tempting quality; fascination; charm; appeal; v. to attract or tempt by something flattering or desirable
examples: But despite her allure, her assiduous assault on New York produced no results.

name: obsession
description: n. the domination of one's thoughts or feelings by a persistent idea, image, desire, etc.
examples: The media's obsession with famous mommies-to-be is no secret, and is certainly nothing new.

name: formidable
description: adj. difficult to deal with or overcome; inspiring respect or wonder because of size, strength, or ability; intimidating
examples: He is a formidable leader of the Pentagon, and he knows how focus and to get things done.

name: summit
description: n. the highest point or part, as of a hill, a line of travel, or any object; top; apex; apogee; a meeting between heads of government or other high-ranking officials to discuss a matter of great importance
examples: Relive the first evening of the summit with photo and video highlights.

name: peak
description: n. the highest or most important point or level; v. to become weak, thin, and sickly
examples: The resulting image is one of the most celebrated pictures of the glamorous and vivacious Diana at the peak of her fame.

name: ascent
description: n. movement upward from a lower to a higher state, degree, grade, or status; advancement
examples: The ascent of the latest dictator-in-waiting spells the death of reform for the Saudi Kingdom.

name: expedition
description: n. an excursion, journey, or voyage made for some specific purpose, as of war or exploration; the group of persons, ships, etc., engaged in such an activity; promptness or speed in accomplishing something
examples: The young prince was at the central London square for the media launch of the expedition.

name: serendipity
description: n. the accidental discovery of something pleasant, valuable, or useful; a natural gift for making pleasant, valuable, or useful discoveries by accident
examples: Then came one of those weird bits of serendipity that make the writing life드nd the book tour등orth all the trouble.

name: prerogative
description: n.a privilege or right that allows a particular person or group to give orders or make decisions or judgments
examples: If President Obama decides he needs a new diplomatic team, that is his prerogative

name: cavalier
description: n.a gallant or chivalrous man, especially one escorting a lady; a horseman, especially a mounted soldier; knight; adj. showing an arrogant or jaunty disregard or lack of respect for something or somebody
examples: Subversive guys with cavalier notions about female consent are nothing new::Not only that, it will look like an admission that the Obama administration truly was cavalier with the safety of children.

name: consent
description: n.permission, approval, or agreement; compliance; acquiescence
examples: He consented to the proposal. We asked her permission, and she consented

name: concurrent
description: adj. occurring or existing simultaneously or side by side; tending to or intersecting at the same point
examples: There is no concurrent sense of tolerance for candidates with liberal or libertarian social positions.

name: belay
description: v. to fasten a rope or line to a securing point on a ship or boat; to stop doing something, or not follow an earlier instruction
examples: Belay that, the meeting will be at 0900 instead of 0800

name: evacuate
description: v. to remove (persons or things) from a place, as a dangerous place or disaster area, for reasons of safety or protection
examples: Two hundred people들ncluding more than 20 newborns등ere forced to evacuate

name: grueling
description: adj. exhausting; very tiring; arduously severe
examples: The grueling January primary gauntlet is in full force, ending with Florida at the end of the month.

name: altitude
description: n. the height of anything above a given planetary reference plane, especially above sea level on earth; a place or region situated high above sea level
examples: It measures air speed듩ot ground speed, but the speed of the airplane at altitude

name: mundane
description: adj. common; ordinary; banal; unimaginative; of or relating to this world or earth as contrasted with heaven; worldly; earthly
examples: The acts ranged from the mundane to the unexpected: Assisted a tourist with directions because he looked lost::After all, it is only by observing people in mundane situations, that we come to know each other

name: penchant
description: n. a strong inclination, taste, or liking for something
examples: Yes, the Nobel Committee does have a penchant for the drama of the moment.
